\c 4
\d (1) For the choir leader, from David: This psalm is to be accompanied by various plucked string instruments.
\b
\q1
\v 1 (2) Answer my call, O God!
\q2 Only You can justify me before all my enemies.
\q1 Before now when I was in trouble, and you helped me.
\q2 Therefore I implore: Have pity on me and listen to my prayer!
\b
\q1
\v 2 (3) Why are you hostile to me, when will you condemn me ?!
\q2 How old are you to slander me?
\qr (interrupted instrumental music) \f + \fr 3: 2 \fk interrupted instrumental music \ft translating the word "selah" in Hebrew. It does not know exactly what it means to 'selah', but most interpreters say that most likely the word is a sign to the music player. 
\F *
\b
\q1
\v 3 (4) Be assured! The Lord has chosen and dedicated those who belong to His people.
\q2 So he must hear when I cry out to him!
\q1
\v 4 (5) Every one of my enemies should fear and do not let himself be carried away by anger.
\q2 Take it easy and think about it at night while lying in bed.
\qr (interrupted by instrumental music)
\b
\q1
\v 5 (6) Offer the proper sacrifice to remove your sins
\q2 and trust in the Lord.
\b
\q1
\v 6 (7) O Lord, so many people complain, "Who can lead us to end this tribulation and the Lord bless us again?"
\q2 Therefore, O Lord, let your kindness be like the light of dawn to shine on us! \f + \fr 4: 6 \fk Your kindness is like light ... 
\ft. Literally, . \f *
\q1
\v 7 (8) But you always delight my heart!
\q2 My joy is greater than the joy of my enemies when the wheat harvest and the wine are over.
\q1
\v 8 (9) With a calm heart I can lie down and sleep.
\q2 And it is only because of you, O Lord, who makes me secure!